# ü¶â What is GitGuardian?

GitGuardian Secrets Detection detects and fixes vulnerabilities in source code at every step of the software development lifecycle, covering 350+ types of secrets like API keys, database connection strings, private keys, certificates, and more. The platform‚Äôs policy engine enables security teams to monitor and enforce rules across their VCS, DevOps tools, and infrastructure-as-code configurations. Our automated remediation playbooks and collaboration features bring security and development teams together to resolve incidents fast and in full.

## 1. Scan your codebase for 350+ types of secrets
GitGuardian scans your GitHub repositories and raises alerts only for critical secrets, such as API keys or other credentials. At scale, GitGuardian‚Äôs detection algorithm has been battle-tested on over three years of activity in all public GitHub repositories ‚Äì totaling over 1 billion scanned commits!

## 2. Quickly remediate your hard-coded secrets
If you ever experience a leak involving a credential, we have a complete remediation guide used by 100k+ developers each year. We‚Äôll show you how to revoke the secret and remove it from your git history.

##  3. Prevent secrets from reaching GitHub
Install ggshield, the GitGuardian CLI, and add secrets detection to your local development workflow using pre-commit and pre-push git hooks integrations.

# üôã‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è FAQ

**What is your pricing?**
GitGuardian is free for teams under 25 developers and offers a 30-day trial for larger teams.

**How can I be sure that GitGuardian won‚Äôt raise too many false positives?**
We have scanned billions of commits, sent millions of alerts since 2018, and integrated each feedback to improve our algorithm. Our alerts currently receive 91% ‚Äútrue positive‚Äù feedback from developers.

**My repositories are private; why should I install automated secret detection?**
Imagine if there were a plain text file with all your credit card numbers inside, you wouldn‚Äôt put this file inside your company‚Äôs git repository. Secrets are just as sensitive and should be handled with special care.

**Is GitGuardian available to be installed on-premise?**
Yes, you can contact one of our security specialists to look over the possibility of installing GitGuardian on-premise on your repositories.

# ‚öíÔ∏è Installation notes 

You should install GitGuardian directly through your [GitGuardian](https://dashboard.gitguardian.com/) workspace on the Integration settings page. 

So that you know, your GitHub organization or GitHub account can only be associated with a single GitGuardian workspace.

# üëã Support

If you experience any difficulties or have any questions, please reach out to us by email ([support@gitguardian.com](mailto:support@gitguardian.com)).

## Walkthrough

This PR implements a comprehensive architectural reorganization of the Rust backend and test suite. Configuration handling is refactored from a monolithic `app_config.rs` into modular pieces (`auth0_config.rs`, `database_config.rs`, `defaults.rs`, `security_config.rs`). Application services are renamed and split: `admin_service` becomes `admin` module with `mapper.rs` and `category.rs` submodules; `equipment_service` becomes `equipment` with `auth.rs` and `mapper.rs`. Error conversions are extracted to a dedicated `conversions.rs` module. Auth0 infrastructure is reorganized into `dtos.rs`, `requests.rs`, and `traits.rs`. Security code is modularized into `cors.rs`, `headers.rs`, `login_throttle.rs`, and `rate_limit.rs`. Repository layer adds submodules for equipment search and photo operations. Pagination support is introduced via `PaginationParams`. The test suite is restructured: monolithic test files (`admin_routes_tests.rs`, `auth0_endpoints_tests.rs`, `core_api_tests.rs`) are removed and replaced with organized test modules and new mock repository implementations. Frontend simplification replaces a dynamic data-fetching home page with static content.

## Possibly related PRs

- **PR `#10`**: Modifies configuration (AppConfig/from_env) and substantially expands test suites for WebSocket lifecycle, Auth0/JIT provisioning, and bootstrapping‚Äîshares overlapping refactoring scope.
- **PR `#8`**: Adjusts configuration fields and rate-limiting/Auth0 security handling, addressing related configuration areas.
- **PR `#9`**: Consolidates test mock infrastructure and Auth0 test scaffolding, directly aligned with test reorganization in this PR.

## Poem

> Config spreads thin, repos split just right,  
> Tests squared away with mocks burning bright,  
> *Twitches nose* ‚Äî a refactor so fine! üêá‚ú®

# Transforming Code Reviews with AI

## Features

**Automated Reviews**: Continuous reviews of the pull requests including incremental commits. 

**Summarization**: Generates high-level summary and a technical walkthrough of the PR changes.¬†

**Line-by-line review**: Provides line-by-line suggestions committable with one click.

**Codebase verification**:  Verifies the impact on the overall codebase and identifies missing changes.

**Insights into your code**:  Ask any questions on your codebase within the pull request 

**Chat about your code** : Chat with the bot around your code.¬†The more you chat, the smarter it gets.

**Issue Validation**:  Validates the PR against the linked issues and identifies other related issues¬†
